e\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JaCoCo Report Issues**\\n\\nI'm looking into the dynamic coverage report generated through JaCoCo, which uses the latest test report file. If the external part didn't run JVM tests after the commit, that might be an issue. I wonder if I need to enable JaCoCo to include classes without specific line numbers. It can instrument classes, but if there's no line number, we might need a workaround. I’ll keep instructions in mind about not broadening patches unnecessarily.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Metadata and Coverage Issues**\\n\\nI’m contemplating whether I could edit metadata since the dynamic access call site shows as \\\"covered\\\" solely based on JaCoCo, without metadata help. Adding resource metadata didn’t improve coverage, but it might be essential for native runtime. Maybe the first commit created the necessary metadata. I’ll look into potential Checkstyle issues too, and I wonder about the implications of native images stripping line numbers. I’m considering if compiling from the source jar in the test project is feasible with necessary dependencies.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Gradle and Source Context**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using Gradle to include source context classes for test implementation, which could replace the library with a compiled version that has debug lines. However, it seems like tests should rely on the external library jar. I wonder if a potential hack could involve dependency substitution to compile JTidy source into the test, but that seems not ideal. I also need to check if the class file source jar is available, despite the artifact lacking debug information.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kVG8CS2kRxv9ftoXrmBDD53g|fc_0cdd004a28d5f22f0169f2910e1b848197810660e4298fba8d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"FRAME_PATTERN|ParsedJacocoReport|coveredLinesBySource|parseJacoco\" tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/